  "texts": [
    "Up to pulling back by f ∈ Aut(Σ), any solution (g ′ B, ρ ′, h ′) that is equivalent to (g B, ρ, h) for (B 2, G/K) is of the form (g B, C φ • ρ, φ • h) = (g B, ρ ′, h ′) for φ ∈ G.Notice that this equivalence class is a union of equivalence classes for the pair (B 2, G 0 /K 0).",
    "Since the map HE 0 → HE sends the G 0 -equivalence class of (g B, ρ, h) in HE 0 to the G-equivalence class of (g B, ρ, h) in HE, the proposition will follow if we show that this union is finite.Let{φ 0 = e, φ 1,..., φ N } ⊂ G be representatives for the G 0 -cosets in G. Any (g B, C φ •ρ, φ•h) = (g B, ρ ′, h ′) is in the G 0 -equivalence class of (g B, C φi • ρ, φ i • h) for some i ∈ {0,..., N }.That is, the number of G 0equivalence classes in any G-equivalence class is at most N. Thus, the proposition follows.□ Finally, we prove the following necessary condition for a soltion (M, g) that satisfies Ansatz 3.1 to be homogeneous.",
    "We will use the contrapositive of this in §4 to prove existence of inhomogeneous solitons coming from Ansatz 3.1.",
    "Lemma 4.11.",
    "If a soliton (M, g) satisfying Ansatz 3.1 is locally homogeneous, then (B, g B) is also locally homogeneous.Proof."
  ],
